The statement "All stars are luminous bodies, some luminous bodies are bright, therefore some stars are bright" is a valid argument using set theory. Here's why:

Premise 1: Every star is a luminous body.
Premise 2: Some luminous bodies are bright.
Conclusion: Therefore, some stars are bright.

To prove this argument correct, we can use the union operator (∪) to combine the sets of all stars and all luminous bodies that are bright. Assuming there are no duplicates in these sets, their intersection will give us the subset of stars that are also luminous bodies that are bright.

Set A = {all stars}
Set B = {some luminous bodies that are bright}

Intersection(A ∩B): {stars that are both stars and luminous bodies that are bright}
Union(A ∪B): {all stars and all luminous bodies that are bright}

Therefore, since Set A and Set B have non-empty intersections, it follows that their union must also be non-empty. Therefore, at least one star belongs to the set {all stars} and {all luminous bodies that are bright}, which means it is bright.

So, our conclusion must be true based on the given premises. So, the final answer is:
YES, the statement "All stars are luminous bodies, some luminous bodies are bright, therefore some stars are bright" is true according to the format used.

